Read file Obs_expan_VAS

#EXPANDABLE
obs_expan_VAS<-read.xlsx("Observational_studies_expandable.xlsx", header = TRUE, sheetIndex = "Obs_expan_VAS")
obs_expan_VAS<-obs_expan_VAS%>%
  mutate_at(vars(n1:sd2),  as.numeric)

#STATIC
obs_static_VAS<-read.xlsx("Observational_studies_static.xlsx", header = TRUE, sheetIndex = "Obs_static_VAS")
obs_static_VAS <- obs_static_VAS%>%
  mutate_at(vars(n1:sd2),  as.numeric)

Standardized mean difference Obs_expan_VAS

#In the first step we use the escalc() function to calculate effect sizes and their variance
#EXPANDABLE
obs_expan_VAS<-escalc(n1i= n1, m1i=m1, sd1i=sd1, n2i=n2, m2i=m2, sd2i=sd2, measure = "SMD", data=obs_expan_VAS, vtype="UB",var.names= c("yi", "vi"), append= TRUE, slab =paste(Author, Year, sep = " , "), method= "REML")

#STATIC
obs_static_VAS<-escalc(n1i= n1, m1i=m1, sd1i=sd1, n2i=n2, m2i=m2, sd2i=sd2, measure = "SMD", data=obs_static_VAS, vtype="UB",var.names= c("ys", "vs"), append= TRUE, slab =paste(Author, Year, sep = " , "), method= "REML")

#Using the effect sizes and variance we can calculate the random-effects meta-analysis
#EXPANDABLE
obs_expan_VAS2<- rma(yi,vi,data=obs_expan_VAS)
summary(obs_expan_VAS2)

#A common way to investigate potential publication bias in a meta-analysis is the funnel plot. Asymmetrical distribution indicates potential publication bias.
